# Cypress Automation Testing Rules

## Project Structure

### File Organization
- **Test Files**: `cypress/e2e/**/*.cy.js` - Organized by feature/module
- **Page Objects**: `cypress/pages/*.js` - One file per page/component
- **Fixtures**: `cypress/fixtures/*.json` - Test data in JSON format
- **Custom Commands**: `cypress/support/commands/**/*.js` - Reusable commands
- **Support**: `cypress/support/e2e.js` - Global configuration

### Naming Conventions
- **Test Files**: Use descriptive names with suffix `-pos.cy.js` (positive) or `-neg.cy.js` (negative)
  - ✅ `login-pos.cy.js`, `forgotpassword-neg.cy.js`
  - ❌ `test1.cy.js`, `loginTest.cy.js`
- **Page Objects**: Use PascalCase with `Page` suffix
  - ✅ `LoginPage.js`, `ForgotPasswordPage.js`
  - ❌ `loginPage.js`, `login.js`
- **Test Descriptions**: Use Indonesian for test case descriptions
  - ✅ `'Login sukses dengan email dan password valid'`
  - ✅ `'Lupa password > Pengecekkan kolom email reset password kosong'`

## Page Object Model (POM)

### Page Object Structure
```javascript
class PageName {
  // 1. Selectors (as getters or class properties)
  get emailInput() {
    return '#email';
  }
  
  // OR as class properties
  emailInput = '#email'

  // 2. Actions (methods that interact with elements)
  visit() {
    cy.visit('/login');
  }

  fillEmail(email) {
    cy.get(this.emailInput)
      .clear()
      .type(email);
  }

  // 3. Assertions (optional, can be in test files)
  verifySuccessMessage(message) {
    cy.get('.success-message').should('contain.text', message);
  }
}

export default new PageName();
```

### Page Object Best Practices
- ✅ Export as singleton instance: `export default new PageName()`
- ✅ Use getters for selectors when logic is needed, properties for simple selectors
- ✅ Group selectors at the top, actions below
- ✅ Methods should be atomic (one action per method)
- ✅ Always use `clear()` before `type()` to avoid flaky tests
- ✅ Include visibility/enabled checks before interactions:
  ```javascript
  clickButton() {
    cy.contains('button', 'Submit')
      .should('be.visible')
      .and('not.be.disabled')
      .click();
  }
  ```

## Test File Structure

### Standard Test Structure
```javascript
import PageObject from '../../pages/PageObject';

describe('Feature Name - Test Type', () => {
  let testData;

  before(() => {
    cy.fixture('fixtureName').then((data) => {
      testData = data;
    });
  });

  beforeEach(() => {
    PageObject.visit();
    cy.url().should('include', '/expected-path');
  });

  it('Test case description in Indonesian', () => {
    const user = testData.validUser;
    
    // Arrange
    PageObject.fillEmail(user.email);
    
    // Act
    PageObject.clickSubmit();
    
    // Assert
    cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');
    cy.screenshot('Capture - Description');
  });
});
```

### Test Organization
- ✅ Group related tests in `describe` blocks by feature
- ✅ Use `before()` for fixture loading
- ✅ Use `beforeEach()` for test setup (navigation, cleanup)
- ✅ One test case per `it()` block
- ✅ Use descriptive test names in Indonesian
- ✅ Separate positive and negative tests into different files

## Fixtures & Test Data

### Fixture Structure
```json
{
  "validUser": {
    "email": "user@example.com",
    "password": "SecurePass123!"
  },
  "invalidUser": {
    "email": "invalid@test.com",
    "password": "wrong"
  }
}
```

### Fixture Usage
- ✅ Load fixtures in `before()` hook
- ✅ Store fixture data in variables: `let users;`
- ✅ Access nested data: `users.validUser.email`
- ✅ Use descriptive names: `validUser`, `invalidUser`, `resetPasswordUser`
- ✅ Keep sensitive data out of fixtures (use environment variables)

## Custom Commands

### Creating Custom Commands
```javascript
// In cypress/support/commands/*.commands.js
Cypress.Commands.add('commandName', (param1, param2) => {
  // Implementation
  cy.get(selector).click();
});

// Usage in tests
cy.commandName(param1, param2);
```

### Custom Command Best Practices
- ✅ Group related commands in separate files: `auth.commands.js`
- ✅ Import commands in `cypress/support/e2e.js`
- ✅ Use descriptive names: `cy.logout()`, `cy.typePassword()`
- ✅ Include error handling and assertions
- ✅ Document complex commands with comments

## Assertions

### Assertion Patterns
```javascript
// URL assertions
cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');

// Element visibility
cy.get('.message').should('be.visible');

// Text content
cy.contains('Success message').should('be.visible');
cy.get('.message').should('contain.text', 'Expected text');

// Form values
cy.get('#email').should('have.value', 'user@example.com');

// Element state
cy.get('#submit').should('not.be.disabled');
cy.get('#remember').should('be.checked');
```

### Assertion Best Practices
- ✅ Use specific selectors over generic ones
- ✅ Chain assertions: `.should('be.visible').and('not.be.disabled')`
- ✅ Use `contains()` for text matching when exact selector is unknown
- ✅ Verify state before interactions
- ✅ Use meaningful error messages in custom assertions

## Screenshots

### Screenshot Usage
```javascript
// Before action
cy.screenshot('Capture - Sebelum Sign In');

// After action
cy.screenshot('Capture - Setelah berhasil Login');

// With descriptive names
cy.screenshot('FAILED-Password validation');
cy.screenshot('PASSED-Login success');
```

### Screenshot Best Practices
- ✅ Use descriptive names in Indonesian/English
- ✅ Capture key moments: before actions, after assertions, on failures
- ✅ Use consistent naming: `'Capture - Description'`
- ✅ Screenshots are automatically captured on failures (configured in `cypress.config.js`)

## API Interception

### Intercept Pattern
```javascript
// Setup intercept
cy.intercept('POST', '**/api/endpoint').as('apiCall');

// Trigger action
PageObject.submitForm();

// Wait and assert
cy.wait('@apiCall').then((interception) => {
  expect(interception.response.statusCode).to.eq(200);
  // Additional assertions
});
```

### Interception Best Practices
- ✅ Use aliases for readability: `.as('apiCall')`
- ✅ Wait for intercepts before assertions
- ✅ Check status codes and response data
- ✅ Handle retries for flaky APIs:
  ```javascript
  function retryApiCall(attempt = 1, maxRetry = 3) {
    cy.intercept('POST', '**/api/endpoint').as('api');
    triggerAction();
    cy.wait('@api').then((interception) => {
      if (interception.response.statusCode !== 200 && attempt < maxRetry) {
        retryApiCall(attempt + 1);
      }
    });
  }
  ```

## Error Handling

### Error Handling Patterns
```javascript
// Retry logic
const MAX_RETRY = 3;
function retryOperation(attempt = 1) {
  cy.intercept('POST', '**/api/endpoint').as('api');
  triggerAction();
  cy.wait('@api').then((interception) => {
    if (interception.response.statusCode === 200) {
      // Success
    } else if (attempt < MAX_RETRY) {
      retryOperation(attempt + 1);
    } else {
      throw new Error('Operation failed after retries');
    }
  });
}

// Error collection in loops
const errors = [];
testCases.forEach((tc) => {
  // Test logic
  if (!found) {
    errors.push(`Failed: ${tc.name}`);
  }
});

// Fail at end if errors exist
cy.then(() => {
  if (errors.length > 0) {
    throw new Error(`Failures:\n${errors.join('\n')}`);
  }
});
```

## Test Data Management

### Test Case Arrays
```javascript
const passwordTestCases = [
  {
    name: 'Password hanya lowercase',
    newPassword: 'password',
    expectedMessage: 'Must contain uppercase'
  },
  // More cases...
];

passwordTestCases.forEach((tc) => {
  cy.log(`Running case: ${tc.name}`);
  // Test logic
});
```

### Best Practices
- ✅ Use data-driven tests for multiple similar cases
- ✅ Store test cases in arrays
- ✅ Include descriptive `name` property
- ✅ Log current test case: `cy.log(\`Running case: ${tc.name}\`)`
- ✅ Collect errors and fail at the end for batch validation

## Waiting & Timing

### Wait Strategies
```javascript
// Wait for element
cy.get('.element', { timeout: 10000 }).should('be.visible');

// Wait for API
cy.wait('@apiCall');

// Explicit wait (use sparingly)
cy.wait(3000); // Only when necessary

// Wait for URL change
cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');
```

### Best Practices
- ✅ Prefer implicit waits (Cypress auto-waits)
- ✅ Use `cy.wait('@alias')` for API calls
- ✅ Avoid `cy.wait(milliseconds)` unless absolutely necessary
- ✅ Use timeouts in selectors for slow elements: `{ timeout: 10000 }`
- ✅ Wait for URL changes after navigation

## Code Quality

### General Rules
- ✅ Use ES6 imports: `import PageObject from '../../pages/PageObject'`
- ✅ Use const/let appropriately
- ✅ Keep test files focused (one feature per file)
- ✅ Extract complex logic into helper functions
- ✅ Comment complex flows or workarounds
- ✅ Remove commented-out code before committing (or document why it's kept)

### Code Organization
- ✅ Group imports at the top
- ✅ Group related code together
- ✅ Use consistent indentation (2 spaces)
- ✅ Use meaningful variable names
- ✅ Keep functions small and focused

## Negative Test Cases

### Negative Test Patterns
```javascript
it('Test case > Validation error message', () => {
  // Clear required field
  PageObject.clearField();
  
  // Submit without required data
  PageObject.submit();
  
  // Assert error message
  cy.contains('Field is required').should('be.visible');
  cy.screenshot();
});
```

### Negative Test Best Practices
- ✅ Test all validation rules
- ✅ Test empty fields
- ✅ Test invalid formats
- ✅ Test boundary values
- ✅ Test error messages are displayed correctly
- ✅ Use descriptive test names: `'Pengecekkan kolom email kosong'`

## Reporting

### Test Reporting
- ✅ Use Mochawesome reporter (configured in `cypress.config.js`)
- ✅ Reports generated in `cypress/reports/run-{timestamp}/`
- ✅ Include screenshots in reports (configured)
- ✅ Use descriptive test names for better report readability

## Common Patterns

### Login Flow
```javascript
LoginPage.visit();
LoginPage.fillEmail(user.email);
LoginPage.clickNext();
LoginPage.fillPassword(user.password);
LoginPage.signIn();
cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');
```

### Logout Flow
```javascript
cy.intercept('POST', '**/logout').as('logout');
cy.logout();
cy.wait('@logout').then((interception) => {
  if (interception.response.statusCode === 200) {
    cy.url().should('include', '/login');
  }
});
```

### Form Submission with Validation
```javascript
// Fill form
PageObject.fillField(value);
PageObject.submit();

// Assert success
cy.url().should('include', '/success');
cy.contains('Success message').should('be.visible');
```
